Preheat your oven to 200 degrees. Chop the @red potato{1} into chunks (leaving the
nutritious skin on). Place on a #baking tray{} and toss in a splash of
@olive oil{} and a good pinch of @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Put on the top shelf
of your #oven{} for ~{25%minutes} or until crispy.

Peel the @cucumber{1} and cut in half lengthways and lengthways again. Slice
along each length to remove and discard the seeds. Grate your cucumber and then
put in a #colander{} in your #sink{} to drain some of the excess water.

Pull the @mint{½}(finely chopped) leaves off their stalks. Discard the stalks and
finely chop the leaves. Mix two-thirds into the @Greek style natural yoghurt{1}
along with your cucumber. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} to taste. This
is your raita!

Stir together the @ras-el-hanout{1.5} and the @flour{1} with a pinch of @salt{}
and @black pepper{}. Coat the @tilapia fillet{2} on all sides with the mixture.

Heat a splash of @olive oil{} in a #non-stick pan{} on high heat. Place your fish
away from yourself into the pan (to avoid sputtering). Cook on one side for
~{2%minutes}, then gently turn over to cook for a further ~{1%minute}.
> If you have some, in the last 30 seconds add a knob of butter and spoon it over as it melts.

Take your potato out of your oven and divide between your plates. Lay your
moroccan spiced fish on top and pour over any juices from the pan. Spoon on a
good dollop of cooling cucumber raita and garnish with your remaining mint.